1
00:01:16,550 --> 00:01:19,985
Target bearing 0-2-0.

2
00:01:20,153 --> 00:01:22,053
Contact 0-2-0.

3
00:01:22,221 --> 00:01:25,520
- Range 20,000.
- Range 20,000 yards.

4
00:01:25,691 --> 00:01:29,649
- Course 2-5-5.
- Course 2-5-5 true.

5
00:01:29,828 --> 00:01:33,228
- Speed 13.
- Speed 13 knots.

6
00:01:33,397 --> 00:01:35,662
Cowboys.

7
00:02:06,159 --> 00:02:09,992
Man the guns.

8
00:02:39,488 --> 00:02:42,252
Enchanter, Mobile.

9
00:02:44,592 --> 00:02:48,187
Well, we're a long way from home.
Wake 'em up!

10
00:02:54,189 --> 00:02:56,016
What's that?

11
00:02:58,026 --> 00:03:00,351
The Navy!

12
00:03:00,529 --> 00:03:03,566
Quick, show the flag!
Hurry up!

13
00:03:13,816 --> 00:03:18,013
Enchanter!
This is the US Coast Guard!

14
00:03:18,187 --> 00:03:21,281
Heave to and prepare to be boarded!

15
00:03:35,135 --> 00:03:39,365
Enchanter! You are a US flagged ship,
and we are going to board you.

16
00:03:39,739 --> 00:03:41,763
Heave to now!

17
00:03:53,250 --> 00:03:56,377
l want to see your crew on the bow.

18
00:04:12,400 --> 00:04:15,664
You two, move forward.

19
00:04:15,835 --> 00:04:18,133
Randall, come with me.

20
00:04:23,109 --> 00:04:26,669
- What do you want?
- Kneel down.

21
00:04:30,048 --> 00:04:34,381
Captain... Captain?

22
00:04:34,551 --> 00:04:36,041
Go ahead, Senior Chief.

23
00:04:36,887 --> 00:04:41,915
lt's a bad one. l think you'd better
send over the video camera.

24
00:04:59,606 --> 00:05:01,973
Jack, come on in.

25
00:05:04,510 --> 00:05:07,707
- How high is the pile on your desk?
- About this high.

26
00:05:07,880 --> 00:05:10,370
- Now it's this high.
- What have you got?

27
00:05:10,549 --> 00:05:15,542
You heard about that business in
the south Caribbean? l need the details.

28
00:05:15,721 --> 00:05:18,018
- By when?
- As soon as you can.

29
00:05:19,489 --> 00:05:22,720
- OK.
- Jack? Be discreet.

30
00:05:24,761 --> 00:05:27,127
What do you mean?

31
00:05:27,297 --> 00:05:29,231
You'll find out.

32
00:05:30,566 --> 00:05:33,262
Mysterious...

33
00:05:35,003 --> 00:05:36,904
l love a mystery.

34
00:05:41,175 --> 00:05:44,234
- Ryan, John P.
- Let him through.

35
00:05:46,680 --> 00:05:49,273
- Here you go.
- Thank you.

36
00:05:49,448 --> 00:05:53,009
- You know where you're going?
- Yes. Thank you.

37
00:05:53,185 --> 00:05:57,519
- Oh, where do l park?
- Right over there.

38
00:06:08,365 --> 00:06:10,594
...main passageway, going forward...

39
00:06:10,767 --> 00:06:13,600
...master stateroom...
blood on the deck...

40
00:06:13,770 --> 00:06:17,501
19 cartridges were recovered...

41
00:06:17,673 --> 00:06:23,269
...as well as
the two weapons that fired them.

42
00:06:23,444 --> 00:06:30,179
The blood samples taken were
consistent with the crew, Hardin...

43
00:06:30,350 --> 00:06:33,808
...and his wife
and his son and daughter.

44
00:06:35,889 --> 00:06:38,413
...blood on sheets and pillows...

45
00:06:38,590 --> 00:06:43,118
...on both starboard and port side racks.
And on the mirror too.

46
00:06:43,295 --> 00:06:48,288
They were killed in their staterooms,
apparently as they slept.

47
00:06:48,466 --> 00:06:50,797
Dragged topside and thrown overboard.

48
00:06:52,302 --> 00:06:57,295
The two men in custody surrendered
after a brief attempt to escape.

49
00:06:57,473 --> 00:07:00,737
What do we know about them?
The men in custody?

50
00:07:03,446 --> 00:07:07,313
Half a dozen arrests for drug
trafficking in Bogota, Mr President.

51
00:07:08,516 --> 00:07:09,847
Drugs.

52
00:07:11,919 --> 00:07:15,184
Suspected ties to the Cali cartel,
not Medellin...

53
00:07:15,356 --> 00:07:16,755
You all right, James?

54
00:07:16,924 --> 00:07:19,050
...according to DEA.

55
00:07:19,225 --> 00:07:21,853
- Why?
- Nothing exotic, sir.

56
00:07:22,028 --> 00:07:25,190
Straight piracy and murder.
lt's not the first time.

57
00:07:27,532 --> 00:07:30,831
lt's the first time it was a friend of mine.

58
00:07:32,603 --> 00:07:34,695
Yes, sir.

59
00:07:41,111 --> 00:07:44,546
- What was that? You all right?
- Yeah.

60
00:07:44,713 --> 00:07:47,272
l haven't slept in 36 hours.
l make any sense?

61
00:07:47,449 --> 00:07:50,976
l don't know. What did you say?
Just kidding. Good job.

62
00:07:54,655 --> 00:08:00,058
- You should give diplomacy lessons.
- To call it as l see it is my job.

63
00:08:00,227 --> 00:08:03,525
- And he's yours.
- Wait for me.

64
00:08:07,700 --> 00:08:09,064
Shut the door.

65
00:08:13,104 --> 00:08:18,041
l promised the American people
l'd do something about the drug problem.

66
00:08:18,208 --> 00:08:20,176
You are.

67
00:08:20,343 --> 00:08:24,473
We support the Colombians' efforts
against the cartels...

68
00:08:24,647 --> 00:08:30,176
We've accomplished nothing. Do these
drug dealers think we're powerless?

69
00:08:30,353 --> 00:08:35,654
That they can keep doing this kind
of thing, and there's no response ever?

70
00:08:37,625 --> 00:08:41,322
Are you suggesting
a course of action, sir?

71
00:08:41,495 --> 00:08:47,296
The course of action l'd suggest
is a course of action l can't suggest.

72
00:09:01,813 --> 00:09:05,339
l'm...not sure where that leaves us.

73
00:09:09,453 --> 00:09:13,218
These drug cartels represent
a clear and present danger

74
00:09:13,389 --> 00:09:17,086
to the national security
of the United States.

75
00:09:52,274 --> 00:09:55,643
- Cortez, Cortez!
- Hello, how are you?

76
00:09:55,819 --> 00:09:59,070
Welcome.
Nice to see you, brother.

77
00:09:59,239 --> 00:10:04,613
I'm waiting,
Throw the ball. You see?

78
00:10:04,787 --> 00:10:07,789
- Like that. I'm ready.
- You know what you've done?

79
00:10:09,625 --> 00:10:11,950
I killed a thief.

80
00:10:12,127 --> 00:10:15,710
I killed a thief
who was stealing from me.

81
00:10:16,590 --> 00:10:18,381
From me!

82
00:10:19,051 --> 00:10:22,302
And his wife, his son
and his daughter.

83
00:10:22,471 --> 00:10:25,224
Apparently without thinking
of the consequences.

84
00:10:25,516 --> 00:10:27,889
Oh yes, sir.

85
00:10:28,060 --> 00:10:33,731
Should I let his children avenge their
father's death when I least expect it'?

86
00:10:33,899 --> 00:10:39,937
He was a good friend and
political ally of the President of the U.S.

87
00:10:48,570 --> 00:10:50,594
That doesn't surprise me.

88
00:10:51,505 --> 00:10:54,997
- lt should at least concern you.
- What can they do?

89
00:10:55,175 --> 00:10:58,474
Come after me? Arrest me?

90
00:10:58,646 --> 00:11:00,806
You're scaring me.

91
00:11:02,348 --> 00:11:07,114
Will you stop long enough
for me to tell you something important?

92
00:11:09,755 --> 00:11:11,620
Thank you.

93
00:11:14,459 --> 00:11:20,862
Listen... You pay me to counsel you,
and l am counselling you.

94
00:11:21,031 --> 00:11:24,796
l'm keeping you alive with information.

95
00:11:24,967 --> 00:11:30,496
lf you disregard my counsel and keep
running your business like this,

96
00:11:30,673 --> 00:11:35,041
with your balls and not your head,
two things will happen.

97
00:11:35,910 --> 00:11:39,346
l'll quit, and you'll get killed.

98
00:11:50,723 --> 00:11:54,783
You forgot to tell me
about your scouting trip.

99
00:11:54,960 --> 00:11:58,622
- No, l didn't.
- You made another contact. Who?

100
00:11:59,331 --> 00:12:02,527
Castro always asked me
about my sources.

101
00:12:02,700 --> 00:12:08,194
- l always gave him the same answer.
- Castro didn't pay you what l pay.

102
00:12:08,371 --> 00:12:11,807
This one will cost you nothing.

103
00:12:13,276 --> 00:12:15,072
A woman.

104
00:12:15,243 --> 00:12:18,542
You're using a woman.

105
00:12:24,618 --> 00:12:27,451
lt won't float.

106
00:12:28,688 --> 00:12:31,623
- John, what do you want? Toast?
- Waffles!

107
00:12:31,791 --> 00:12:35,317
- No time for waffles.
- Anybody seen my keys?

108
00:12:35,494 --> 00:12:38,190
On the front hall table or in your pocket.

109
00:12:38,364 --> 00:12:41,423
- Where are my keys?
- Pancakes!

110
00:12:41,599 --> 00:12:45,126
- Toast, please!
- Thank you.

111
00:12:45,302 --> 00:12:48,430
- Bye, pal.
- Daddy. lt won't float!

112
00:12:48,605 --> 00:12:54,600
lt's not supposed to float,
it's a submarine. lt goes under water.

113
00:12:57,313 --> 00:12:59,338
Hello?

114
00:13:01,282 --> 00:13:02,613
When?

115
00:13:05,053 --> 00:13:07,520
l thought l had the flu.

116
00:13:07,688 --> 00:13:11,351
l'd still think so
if they weren't telling me otherwise.

117
00:13:13,426 --> 00:13:17,055
What are they telling you?

118
00:13:17,229 --> 00:13:23,190
Pancreatic cancer of an aggressive
nature, if l heard them right.

119
00:13:23,368 --> 00:13:26,461
Well, what does it mean?

120
00:13:27,371 --> 00:13:29,896
l guess it means l'm in big trouble.

121
00:13:30,574 --> 00:13:35,101
- l mean, can they operate, or...?
- Maybe.

122
00:13:35,279 --> 00:13:40,944
That's what they said, ''maybe'', which
sounds suspiciously like ''no'' to me.

123
00:13:41,117 --> 00:13:43,584
There's one of them now.

124
00:13:45,587 --> 00:13:49,044
Hey, l'm not dead yet.

125
00:13:50,091 --> 00:13:55,392
l am in a hospital, which means
that l'm not in my office,

126
00:13:55,562 --> 00:13:57,587
which means
l don't know what's going on.

127
00:13:58,231 --> 00:14:00,790
- l need you there.
- Where?

128
00:14:00,966 --> 00:14:04,800
- ln my office, doing my job.
- Wait...

129
00:14:04,970 --> 00:14:08,461
l hate not knowing
what's going on, you know that.

130
00:14:08,640 --> 00:14:11,541
l wouldn't know how to do your job, sir.

131
00:14:11,710 --> 00:14:16,146
You've been around.
You've been to the White House.

132
00:14:16,313 --> 00:14:19,941
- Once. l hated it.
- No, you didn't.

133
00:14:21,217 --> 00:14:25,176
Want to know about politics
in Washington? Four words...

134
00:14:25,354 --> 00:14:27,083
''Watch your back, Jack.''

135
00:14:33,127 --> 00:14:38,588
Bobby, you should be the first to know,
or the third or fourth...

136
00:14:38,765 --> 00:14:41,963
Ryan is to be acting
Deputy Director of lntelligence.

137
00:14:42,136 --> 00:14:47,595
lt will be a provisional appointment,
of course, until James recovers.

138
00:14:47,774 --> 00:14:51,436
You brief him
on our aid programme to Colombia.

139
00:14:51,610 --> 00:14:56,512
He has to talk the Oversight Committee
out of another 75 million dollars.

140
00:14:56,681 --> 00:15:00,047
And not make a complete fool
out of himself.

141
00:15:02,152 --> 00:15:04,313
What about the Hardin murders?

142
00:15:04,487 --> 00:15:08,082
l'm on it. The President's calling
for a full-court press.

143
00:15:08,257 --> 00:15:13,251
So, you guys are going to be
working together hand in hand.

144
00:15:14,529 --> 00:15:16,394
That's great.

145
00:15:31,811 --> 00:15:34,142
Margaret...

146
00:15:34,312 --> 00:15:38,214
- Why don't we leave all his things?
- OK.

147
00:15:50,226 --> 00:15:53,093
Ryan. l can't believe it!

148
00:15:53,263 --> 00:15:56,959
He's not a team player,
is that what you're saying?

149
00:15:57,132 --> 00:15:59,066
He's a Boy Scout.

150
00:16:00,034 --> 00:16:05,597
A goddamn Boy Scout. Believes in
loyalty, cleanliness and knot-tying.

151
00:16:05,773 --> 00:16:08,002
So leave him out of it.

152
00:16:08,175 --> 00:16:12,076
He's the Deputy Director of
lntelligence. That will be tricky.

153
00:16:12,245 --> 00:16:14,838
What does he need to know?

154
00:16:15,014 --> 00:16:20,974
Nothing. He needs to know nothing.
He's going to know nothing.

155
00:16:21,987 --> 00:16:24,284
l want a copy
of the President's authorisation

156
00:16:24,455 --> 00:16:27,446
of this new action against the cartels.

157
00:16:28,459 --> 00:16:32,087
- You want what?
- You heard me.

158
00:16:33,497 --> 00:16:35,020
He doesn't know about it.

159
00:16:37,166 --> 00:16:43,195
Let me explain it to you very simply.
This is your deal. Not mine.

160
00:16:43,371 --> 00:16:48,398
Unless l have written authorisation,
this thing is over before it begins.

161
00:16:48,576 --> 00:16:53,639
l'm not going to be the only one left
without a chair when the music stops.

162
00:17:34,415 --> 00:17:37,975
Reciprocity. That's a clever name for it.

163
00:17:38,151 --> 00:17:42,349
Revenge is a very, very,
very dangerous motivation.

164
00:17:44,290 --> 00:17:50,195
Are you able to handle this operation
or not? l'm looking for a yes or no.

165
00:17:50,362 --> 00:17:53,331
You're looking for a political mess.

166
00:17:53,497 --> 00:17:56,295
- Yes or no?
- ls that what they want?

167
00:17:56,467 --> 00:18:00,926
They want what every first-term
administration wants. A second term.

168
00:18:02,472 --> 00:18:05,669
l don't imagine the boys on the Hill
have approved this.

169
00:18:11,513 --> 00:18:13,208
Have they?

170
00:18:15,383 --> 00:18:17,317
ls that a ''no''?

171
00:18:23,423 --> 00:18:25,653
Shit.

172
00:18:25,825 --> 00:18:31,626
l want the money in my account
before l move an inch.

173
00:18:31,797 --> 00:18:35,095
- You got it.
- l need a ComSat link.

174
00:18:35,266 --> 00:18:37,598
- An insertion team.
- Have a brigade.

175
00:18:37,769 --> 00:18:42,330
l don't want a brigade. Just 12 men
who understand discretionary warfare.

176
00:18:42,506 --> 00:18:46,306
- Special Ops people, Spanish-speaking.
- Cutter will get the military.

177
00:18:53,349 --> 00:18:56,010
- How are you today, sir?
- Very well.

178
00:18:56,184 --> 00:18:59,347
- The purpose of your visit?
- Business.

179
00:18:59,521 --> 00:19:02,251
- What business are you in?
- l sell tractors.

180
00:19:02,424 --> 00:19:04,323
l build them, then l sell them.

181
00:19:05,893 --> 00:19:09,852
- And how long will you be staying?
- A few days.

182
00:19:37,686 --> 00:19:41,383
l know it's a risk,
but what's the alternative?

183
00:19:41,557 --> 00:19:46,186
Zapping a retina with 6,000 rads
of cobalt? Not a pretty picture.

184
00:19:46,361 --> 00:19:49,386
Prettier than a tumour
spreading in the cranial sack.

185
00:19:49,564 --> 00:19:51,588
What is her name?

186
00:19:54,166 --> 00:19:57,465
Listen... Hungry?

187
00:19:57,636 --> 00:20:01,732
- Starved.
- We could forget about lunch.

188
00:20:01,907 --> 00:20:06,707
- We did that last time, remember?
- Do l remember? Do you?

189
00:20:08,546 --> 00:20:12,242
- Vaguely.
- Maybe l should refresh your memory.

190
00:20:14,551 --> 00:20:17,611
- Maybe you should.
- Your table is ready now.

191
00:20:17,787 --> 00:20:20,779
- We don't need it. l'll get a cab.
- Moira?

192
00:20:20,957 --> 00:20:26,451
- Hi! How are you? How's Jack?
- He's great, just great.

193
00:20:26,627 --> 00:20:29,620
- You still with the FBl?
- The Director's office.

194
00:20:29,798 --> 00:20:32,392
- Who was that?
- My new friend.

195
00:20:32,566 --> 00:20:35,535
Señor Roberto Landa.

196
00:20:35,703 --> 00:20:39,763
- Doesn't he look like Jack?
- Does he? l can't quite see.

197
00:20:39,939 --> 00:20:44,501
- Only Latin.
- A Latin Jack? This l have to see.

198
00:20:45,544 --> 00:20:48,012
l have to go. Bye.

199
00:20:49,981 --> 00:20:54,441
Well, we know it's not piracy.
Pirates steal boats.

200
00:20:55,119 --> 00:20:59,612
They had plane tickets to Bogota
the morning after the killings.

201
00:20:59,790 --> 00:21:01,382
- Hey, Dan.
- How's it going?

202
00:21:01,558 --> 00:21:04,925
We're sneaking up on a motive.
Dan Murray, FBl.

203
00:21:05,095 --> 00:21:07,995
- Ralph Williams, DEA.
- Said anything yet?

204
00:21:08,164 --> 00:21:12,566
- Yeah, ''We're innocent.''
- Till the D.A. offers them a deal.

205
00:21:12,734 --> 00:21:16,191
He already has. Regular or extra crispy.

206
00:21:16,370 --> 00:21:19,669
Either referring to fried chicken
or the electric chair.

207
00:21:20,474 --> 00:21:22,566
Are you picturing a hit?

208
00:21:22,742 --> 00:21:27,145
On a respectable American
businessman and his family?

209
00:21:28,047 --> 00:21:30,810
You're assuming he's respectable.

210
00:21:39,224 --> 00:21:44,957
We have memos,
letters, credit card statements...

211
00:21:45,129 --> 00:21:50,498
...phone bills, everything
you could need to break his code.

212
00:21:50,666 --> 00:21:53,794
- What's this?
- Old high school yearbook.

213
00:21:53,969 --> 00:21:57,961
- Sweethearts, football team...
- You think?

214
00:21:58,139 --> 00:22:02,838
- l don't know.
- OK, let's see what we've got.

215
00:22:03,010 --> 00:22:05,341
- No cream?
- There wasn't any.

216
00:22:06,114 --> 00:22:10,105
Let's start with birthdays.
Bet your ATM code is your birthday.

217
00:22:10,283 --> 00:22:13,275
- Close.
- ln reverse?

218
00:22:14,954 --> 00:22:17,354
All right, his birthday is...

219
00:22:18,823 --> 00:22:24,226
That would be too easy, wouldn't it?
Try it in reverse.

220
00:22:24,394 --> 00:22:27,022
No. His wife's?

221
00:22:28,165 --> 00:22:29,757
No. His son's?

222
00:22:29,933 --> 00:22:32,196
- This could take...
- Months.

223
00:22:32,368 --> 00:22:34,268
Son's in reverse. This is for you.

224
00:22:36,939 --> 00:22:39,930
No. Wife's in reverse.

225
00:22:40,108 --> 00:22:42,167
No. Daughter's in reverse.

226
00:22:42,343 --> 00:22:45,335
You've got to change your ATM code.

227
00:22:52,886 --> 00:22:54,217
l got it!

228
00:22:54,654 --> 00:22:56,416
l got it!

229
00:23:07,265 --> 00:23:10,894
Wife's birth month,
daughter's day, son's year.

230
00:23:11,068 --> 00:23:13,934
But not in reverse. Sorry.

231
00:23:21,343 --> 00:23:24,607
Print me out that one, will you?

232
00:23:24,779 --> 00:23:26,873
Good boy.

233
00:23:27,048 --> 00:23:31,610
Three years ago, Hardin received
a large infusion of foreign money,

234
00:23:31,785 --> 00:23:37,017
which he invested wisely
in 20 major shopping centres in the US.

235
00:23:37,191 --> 00:23:41,650
l say wisely because in the middle of
the recession, he posted record profits.

236
00:23:41,827 --> 00:23:46,195
At least to the lRS, who he apparently
feared more than his own partners.

237
00:23:46,365 --> 00:23:49,060
According to the figures he gave them...

238
00:23:50,802 --> 00:23:53,964
...the shopping centres
weren't doing so well.

239
00:23:54,138 --> 00:23:58,733
But he was just skimming most of
the profits, 650 million dollars,

240
00:23:58,908 --> 00:24:02,867
and putting it in numbered accounts
in Luxembourg, Panama

241
00:24:03,046 --> 00:24:07,983
and the Cayman lslands.
They killed him for it.

242
00:24:08,150 --> 00:24:09,981
Who?

243
00:24:10,152 --> 00:24:13,416
- His partners.
- Who were his partners?

244
00:24:13,588 --> 00:24:20,083
lt seems clear that he was laundering
money for the Colombian drug cartels.

245
00:24:20,260 --> 00:24:26,289
Jesus... l knew the man for 40 years.
We went to school together.

246
00:24:26,932 --> 00:24:29,526
We almost went into business together.

247
00:24:29,701 --> 00:24:32,761
That would have been good.

248
00:24:33,838 --> 00:24:36,830
The press is going
to have a field-day with this.

249
00:24:37,007 --> 00:24:41,671
- No one outside this room knows.
- They will. They always do.

250
00:24:41,845 --> 00:24:46,748
lt will come out, you're right about that.
And when it does, we'll...

251
00:24:46,917 --> 00:24:51,751
...downplay your relationship
with Hardin somehow.

252
00:24:53,856 --> 00:24:55,550
- What?
- What?

253
00:24:55,724 --> 00:24:59,454
- We'll defuse it.
- Do you disagree?

254
00:24:59,627 --> 00:25:01,390
No.

255
00:25:01,562 --> 00:25:06,498
Well, actually, yes.
l would go in the other direction.

256
00:25:06,666 --> 00:25:11,729
lf a reporter asked if you and Hardin
were friends, l'd say ''good friends''.

257
00:25:11,904 --> 00:25:16,636
lf they asked if you were good friends,
l'd say ''lifelong friends''.

258
00:25:16,808 --> 00:25:22,370
Give them no place to go,
nothing to report. No story.

259
00:25:24,548 --> 00:25:29,416
l mean, it's no sense in
defusing a bomb after it's already...

260
00:25:30,754 --> 00:25:33,381
...it's already gone off.

261
00:25:56,809 --> 00:25:59,073
- Damn.
- Shit.

262
00:26:00,378 --> 00:26:01,709
Do you see him?

263
00:26:02,981 --> 00:26:06,780
All right. Move your team
two metres to the left.

264
00:26:10,287 --> 00:26:13,084
That's it. Stop.

265
00:26:13,256 --> 00:26:17,283
Touch that light-coloured grass.
Sniper at your feet.

266
00:26:18,828 --> 00:26:20,420
Nothing here, Sergeant Major.

267
00:26:20,863 --> 00:26:23,695
- Damn!
- He is good.

268
00:26:40,679 --> 00:26:44,808
That was close.
How's he moving so fast?

269
00:26:49,687 --> 00:26:53,623
l see him. Come in.
Straight in. Now. Run!

270
00:26:55,159 --> 00:26:57,251
Keep coming.

271
00:26:58,862 --> 00:27:03,026
To your left. To your left.

272
00:27:04,266 --> 00:27:07,792
And stop. Sniper at your feet.

273
00:27:09,804 --> 00:27:11,236
What is it?

274
00:27:15,242 --> 00:27:16,766
He had lunch here.

275
00:27:18,011 --> 00:27:22,947
McDonald's quarter-pounder
with cheese.

276
00:27:23,416 --> 00:27:25,849
Damn.

277
00:27:30,989 --> 00:27:33,924
- Damn!
- That's four.

278
00:27:34,826 --> 00:27:38,692
All right, you won this one.
Come on out!

279
00:27:40,564 --> 00:27:43,657
Soldier, how did you get
that close to me?

280
00:27:43,833 --> 00:27:49,169
Sniper approached instructor by being
a sneaky bastard, Sergeant Major!

281
00:27:49,339 --> 00:27:53,501
Do you know the fine for littering
in California, Chavez?

282
00:27:53,674 --> 00:27:55,938
Yes, sir!

283
00:27:58,579 --> 00:28:02,310
l saw you on the sniper course.
You looked good.

284
00:28:02,482 --> 00:28:06,009
- Just about finished here, Sergeant?
- Yes, sir.

285
00:28:06,186 --> 00:28:09,951
Looking forward to taking
some leave with your wife and kids?

286
00:28:10,990 --> 00:28:14,823
- Don't have any wife or kids, sir.
- What do you have?

287
00:28:15,760 --> 00:28:22,290
You don't call anybody often,
you don't write or receive many letters.

288
00:28:25,101 --> 00:28:27,662
Who are you, sir, if l may ask?

289
00:28:27,837 --> 00:28:32,399
Mr Clark and l are putting together
a mission. My team is a part of it.

290
00:28:33,141 --> 00:28:37,509
You'll be gone up to six months,
after which, if you're not dead,

291
00:28:37,679 --> 00:28:41,307
you'll have a choice
of assignments in Special Ops.

292
00:28:57,663 --> 00:29:02,566
...defusing an issue that was
snowballing into another scandal.

293
00:29:03,334 --> 00:29:07,531
The New York Times is reporting that
you and Hardin were good friends?

294
00:29:07,704 --> 00:29:11,834
No, not good friends.
We were lifelong friends.

295
00:29:12,008 --> 00:29:15,875
l said that. l said that.

296
00:29:18,013 --> 00:29:19,776
l told him to say that.

297
00:29:20,416 --> 00:29:24,215
- What?
- l didn't say anything.

298
00:29:24,386 --> 00:29:27,877
- But you were thinking something.
- No.

299
00:29:28,055 --> 00:29:32,389
l was just distracted by the trouble
you were having with your ensemble.

300
00:29:33,993 --> 00:29:38,760
Well, it's not every day
you have to look trustworthy.

301
00:29:38,931 --> 00:29:42,264
- Who told who to say what?
- lt's not important.

302
00:29:43,803 --> 00:29:46,703
- The President?
- Yeah.

303
00:29:46,872 --> 00:29:51,069
Mom says she makes more money
than the President.

304
00:29:51,242 --> 00:29:54,210
She's probably right. Bye.

305
00:30:02,885 --> 00:30:07,083
Thank you, Dr Ryan,
for the information you've shared with us.

306
00:30:08,189 --> 00:30:11,454
- Thank you, Senator.
- We must help the Colombians

307
00:30:11,627 --> 00:30:16,120
in their struggle to curtail
the drug cartels' activities.

308
00:30:16,296 --> 00:30:22,598
However, l'm confused.
How do you see additional funds alone

309
00:30:22,768 --> 00:30:25,601
advancing this programme
from the failure that it is?

310
00:30:25,770 --> 00:30:30,070
- You see what l'm getting at?
- No, l'm afraid l don't.

311
00:30:30,275 --> 00:30:33,641
You said this effort would be
totally benign on our part.

312
00:30:33,810 --> 00:30:38,838
The finding clearly states our assistance
is limited to supply and advice only.

313
00:30:39,016 --> 00:30:40,415
l've read that.

314
00:30:40,584 --> 00:30:45,384
l've also read a similar finding
written 35 years ago

315
00:30:45,555 --> 00:30:49,651
regarding a little-thought-of
sliver of jungle in south-east Asia.

316
00:30:49,825 --> 00:30:56,023
Sorry, you're comparing our request
for anti-drug funds to Vietnam?

317
00:30:56,197 --> 00:31:00,188
l'm comparing it to every time
a committee such as this is asked

318
00:31:00,367 --> 00:31:04,804
to render judgement
based on less than all the facts.

319
00:31:07,874 --> 00:31:10,706
l'm afraid l don't know
what to say to that.

320
00:31:10,876 --> 00:31:14,073
You could assure us
we've been given all the facts.

321
00:31:14,246 --> 00:31:16,076
l thought l had.

322
00:31:16,247 --> 00:31:21,651
You could further assure us, then,
that this increase in funds

323
00:31:21,819 --> 00:31:25,219
will not be used for
any covert military action.

324
00:31:26,022 --> 00:31:29,253
l don't know how you're getting to this.

325
00:31:29,426 --> 00:31:32,588
Long experience, sir.

326
00:31:32,761 --> 00:31:34,456
No troops, then?

327
00:31:34,629 --> 00:31:40,499
l enunciate that clearly because
l don't want there to be any mistake.

328
00:31:40,667 --> 00:31:42,192
No troops.

329
00:31:43,271 --> 00:31:46,103
You could say l have your word on that?

330
00:31:46,273 --> 00:31:48,833
You could indeed, because you do.

331
00:32:04,521 --> 00:32:11,016
Listen up! Dog tags...
Take them off, pass them forward.

332
00:32:11,195 --> 00:32:16,893
Check your pockets for anything
that can be used for identification.

333
00:32:24,839 --> 00:32:26,170
We're feet dry.

334
00:32:40,219 --> 00:32:43,382
Landing zone in sight. Get ready.

335
00:32:43,555 --> 00:32:46,421
Good luck, boys. Go get 'em.

336
00:32:50,360 --> 00:32:52,521
OK, let's take her down now.

337
00:34:39,620 --> 00:34:40,951
Hey, Bob.

338
00:34:43,424 --> 00:34:45,687
- How you doing?
- Good, sir.

339
00:34:47,026 --> 00:34:48,822
Good to see you.

340
00:34:54,933 --> 00:34:58,333
- Morning, Jack.
- Ryan! Come on in.

341
00:34:59,004 --> 00:35:01,267
- Do you know everyone?
- Yes, yes.

342
00:35:01,439 --> 00:35:04,635
- Coffee? Bagel?
- Coffee. Black, please.

343
00:35:05,843 --> 00:35:09,243
- How's the family?
- Good, sir.

344
00:35:09,412 --> 00:35:12,778
- When do l meet the other Dr Ryan?
- She's dying to meet you, sir.

345
00:35:12,948 --> 00:35:15,007
Good, good. Sit down.

346
00:35:21,790 --> 00:35:25,987
- The cash is still there?
- Sir?

347
00:35:26,160 --> 00:35:30,324
- ln Hardin's off-shore accounts.
- 650 million dollars.

348
00:35:30,496 --> 00:35:32,657
- And change.
- And change...

349
00:35:32,832 --> 00:35:36,268
- And we have the account numbers.
- Yes, sir.

350
00:35:36,434 --> 00:35:41,736
Well, what are we waiting for?
Let's get it.

351
00:35:41,907 --> 00:35:45,967
Let's turn this thing around.
650 million dollars and change.

352
00:35:46,143 --> 00:35:49,670
lt's worth ten times that
in political capital.

353
00:35:52,148 --> 00:35:54,776
What?

354
00:35:54,951 --> 00:36:02,413
Well... This connection between
Hardin and the cartels is a theory.

355
00:36:02,591 --> 00:36:04,990
- Theory?
- A theory of mine.

356
00:36:05,159 --> 00:36:09,027
- lt's a theory?
- Well, l know the money is there.

357
00:36:09,197 --> 00:36:13,860
But who exactly Hardin
was working for, l don't know.

358
00:36:14,034 --> 00:36:19,630
l think we would have to establish
that before we could seize the money.

359
00:36:22,641 --> 00:36:25,734
So go down there. Establish it.

360
00:36:25,911 --> 00:36:28,378
- Go where?
- Colombia.

361
00:36:30,582 --> 00:36:32,880
Who, me?

362
00:36:36,420 --> 00:36:41,187
l leave you alone for two weeks,
and you walk into a big bear trap.

363
00:36:41,358 --> 00:36:43,348
l don't know what l was thinking.

364
00:36:43,526 --> 00:36:49,828
You were thinking about impressing
the President. You shouldn't do that.

365
00:36:49,998 --> 00:36:53,297
- November.
- January.

366
00:36:53,468 --> 00:36:55,230
Of last year.

367
00:36:58,372 --> 00:37:02,933
There's a guy down there,
at least used to be... Clark.

368
00:37:03,909 --> 00:37:06,344
We go way back. Good man.

369
00:37:06,945 --> 00:37:09,436
lf you hit a brick wall, look him up.

370
00:37:10,449 --> 00:37:12,917
Admiral Greer?

371
00:37:13,085 --> 00:37:17,111
- Chemotherapy.
- Oh, shit.

372
00:37:17,288 --> 00:37:19,654
Here we go again.

373
00:37:20,891 --> 00:37:23,257
How's Ritter behaving?

374
00:37:23,426 --> 00:37:27,122
Ritter's Ritter. He's leaving me alone.

375
00:37:27,296 --> 00:37:31,494
Are you sure? Watch him like a hawk.

376
00:37:31,667 --> 00:37:34,157
- How are you feeling today?
- OK.

377
00:37:34,336 --> 00:37:39,863
We'll get you in a room, give you
warm blankets, get you lying down.

378
00:37:40,040 --> 00:37:45,341
And then we'll get you back
to your room and get you comfortable...

379
00:38:38,057 --> 00:38:41,321
Variable, this is Knife,
stand by to copy, over.

380
00:38:44,127 --> 00:38:47,325
Variable, this is Knife,
stand by to copy, over.

381
00:38:47,498 --> 00:38:51,524
Knife, this is Variable,
your signal is five by five, over.

382
00:38:54,972 --> 00:38:56,939
Clear.

383
00:39:20,625 --> 00:39:22,718
The chicken is in the pot. Over.

384
00:39:24,796 --> 00:39:27,559
- Cook it.
- Roger that.

385
00:39:44,313 --> 00:39:47,907
Honey? l'm late.

386
00:39:49,384 --> 00:39:51,511
Have a good trip.

387
00:39:52,887 --> 00:39:55,582
l'm not gonna say it.

388
00:39:55,756 --> 00:39:57,724
Don't.

389
00:39:57,891 --> 00:40:00,120
Be careful.

390
00:40:27,550 --> 00:40:34,113
Local time is, well, actually, it's
the same as Washington, 11.16 a.m.

391
00:40:34,289 --> 00:40:37,780
Temperature is
69 degrees Fahrenheit...

392
00:40:44,397 --> 00:40:46,660
Doctor Ryan!

393
00:40:56,040 --> 00:40:59,600
DEA Special Agent Jean Fowler.
How you doing?

394
00:40:59,776 --> 00:41:01,903
- First time in Bogota?
- Yeah.

395
00:41:02,079 --> 00:41:06,640
Let's not stand here
and let someone take a shot at you.

396
00:41:23,263 --> 00:41:26,699
- And these two?
- They're brothers.

397
00:41:29,735 --> 00:41:33,831
Don't do that. Give Dr Ryan
a bit more air back here, please.

398
00:41:34,006 --> 00:41:35,905
Bulletproof.

399
00:41:43,447 --> 00:41:47,247
We don't have a picture.
Escobedo's intelligence officer.

400
00:41:47,785 --> 00:41:50,412
We don't have a name either,
but we know he exists.

401
00:41:51,588 --> 00:41:54,352
The invisible man?

402
00:41:55,191 --> 00:41:57,750
Gently, gently. With your hands.

403
00:41:57,926 --> 00:42:01,088
Luis, put your hands together.

404
00:42:01,963 --> 00:42:04,761
No, your hands together!

405
00:42:07,801 --> 00:42:10,497
Luis, watch the canter!

406
00:42:11,605 --> 00:42:14,596
Yes, very good!

407
00:42:22,915 --> 00:42:25,644
We lost another plane.

408
00:42:32,456 --> 00:42:36,414
- Who is doing this?
- lf l had to guess...

409
00:42:36,593 --> 00:42:40,153
No, l did not ask you to guess.
l can guess.

410
00:42:41,830 --> 00:42:44,025
Someone's been talking
to the drug police.

411
00:42:44,199 --> 00:42:48,932
lmpossible. lf anyone spoke to the
police, l'd be the first to know.

412
00:42:49,104 --> 00:42:51,128
Ernesto!

413
00:42:52,840 --> 00:42:57,867
ls one of the others trying to ruin me,
after what l did to the American?

414
00:42:58,044 --> 00:43:03,572
l guess that wasn't quite
the deterrent you thought it would be.

415
00:43:03,749 --> 00:43:05,717
Find out who it is.

416
00:43:13,958 --> 00:43:16,188
What do you make of this, Colonel?

417
00:43:17,828 --> 00:43:19,488
An opportunity.

418
00:43:22,131 --> 00:43:24,224
An opportunity, Sipo.

419
00:43:38,612 --> 00:43:41,944
- Good afternoon.
- Messages, please?

420
00:43:43,783 --> 00:43:48,219
- Dr Ryan?
- Clark? Sorry l'm late.

421
00:43:48,387 --> 00:43:50,650
l've got ten minutes.

422
00:43:53,024 --> 00:43:57,289
l'm positive Hardin was tied into
the cartels. lt's drug money.

423
00:43:57,461 --> 00:44:01,056
- But you can't prove it.
- So far.

424
00:44:02,799 --> 00:44:06,166
- Mind if l ask you a question?
- No.

425
00:44:06,336 --> 00:44:12,570
Why are you telling me all this?
l've been out of the game for a long time.

426
00:44:14,610 --> 00:44:19,875
l was told that you were wired in,
that you knew the town, the people.

427
00:44:20,046 --> 00:44:23,538
- That you were a player.
- Who told you that?

428
00:44:25,419 --> 00:44:26,908
Jim Greer.

429
00:44:29,389 --> 00:44:30,720
How's he doing?

430
00:44:33,859 --> 00:44:36,259
He's not good.

431
00:44:37,695 --> 00:44:39,686
lt's cancer.

432
00:44:39,864 --> 00:44:41,888
Terminal.

433
00:44:44,102 --> 00:44:47,764
- He's a good man.
- The best.

434
00:44:54,577 --> 00:44:56,908
You a coffee drinker, Dr Ryan?

435
00:45:00,282 --> 00:45:04,047
- Yeah, l like coffee.
- Try the Lindo brand.

436
00:45:04,218 --> 00:45:07,585
- Lindo?
- l think you'll like it.

437
00:45:13,759 --> 00:45:17,127
Mr president, l've got some good news.

438
00:45:17,297 --> 00:45:23,859
Hardin's partner here was someone
you may know of. Ernesto Escobedo.

439
00:45:24,036 --> 00:45:27,835
- Figures.
- ls this another of your theories?

440
00:45:28,538 --> 00:45:34,340
No, sir. We can call this one fact.
Escobedo, like every drug lord here,

441
00:45:34,511 --> 00:45:39,880
also had legitimate businesses.
Hardin was doing business with them.

442
00:45:40,482 --> 00:45:45,350
lmporting among other things,
coffee, which means nothing,

443
00:45:45,520 --> 00:45:52,015
but he was paying too much for
this coffee. 6,200 dollars a pound.

444
00:45:52,192 --> 00:45:55,719
- That's expensive coffee.
- l'd have to agree.

445
00:45:55,896 --> 00:45:58,729
This is good news. l think this does it.

446
00:45:59,365 --> 00:46:02,801
Sir, l also have some other news
which is not so good.

447
00:46:03,703 --> 00:46:05,294
Oh, God...

448
00:46:05,471 --> 00:46:11,567
The DEA feels that the government
here would want the seized funds.

449
00:46:11,743 --> 00:46:16,610
- Or at least a large portion.
- This is our money.

450
00:46:16,780 --> 00:46:20,579
- We found it.
- We could try telling them that.

451
00:46:20,750 --> 00:46:24,151
Try? Tell them.
Or don't tell them, l don't care.

452
00:46:24,787 --> 00:46:29,018
- Sir, with all due respect...
- This is our money, tell them that.

453
00:46:29,190 --> 00:46:34,253
l wouldn't know what to say
or where to start, l'm not a negotiator.

454
00:46:34,428 --> 00:46:36,726
Don't you know someone there?

455
00:46:36,897 --> 00:46:39,626
l went to school
with their Attorney General.

456
00:46:39,799 --> 00:46:44,429
Jacobs will come down.
He'll negotiate. This is our money.

457
00:46:45,605 --> 00:46:47,162
Thank...

458
00:46:48,374 --> 00:46:50,171
Thank you.

459
00:46:53,344 --> 00:46:56,279
l hate this job.

460
00:48:13,412 --> 00:48:15,607
Eyes up!

461
00:48:17,983 --> 00:48:19,950
Demo Team, up!

462
00:48:27,057 --> 00:48:29,321
Fire in the hole!

463
00:48:33,796 --> 00:48:37,664
Let's go, let's go!
Move out! Go, go, go!

464
00:48:58,951 --> 00:49:01,181
Whoever did this is dead.

465
00:49:02,787 --> 00:49:07,349
Whoever did this to me is dead!

466
00:49:07,525 --> 00:49:12,895
Do you hear me?
Are you listening to me?

467
00:49:27,175 --> 00:49:30,941
Mr Jacobs, could you sign these
before you leave?

468
00:49:32,146 --> 00:49:37,515
Moira... Why don't you
call in sick tomorrow?

469
00:49:37,684 --> 00:49:41,016
And the next day. l won't tell anybody.

470
00:49:41,187 --> 00:49:43,883
Even when you're not here,
there's plenty to do.

471
00:49:44,624 --> 00:49:48,252
- Your itinerary.
- You're arguing with me about this?

472
00:49:49,194 --> 00:49:53,357
You work too hard. Adios.

473
00:50:31,964 --> 00:50:34,796
- Landa & Landa.
- Roberto Landa, please.

474
00:50:34,966 --> 00:50:39,630
- This is Moira Wolfson.
- One moment, please.

475
00:50:39,804 --> 00:50:43,432
l think he's on the factory floor.

476
00:50:48,811 --> 00:50:52,246
- Yes?
- A Moira Wolfson is calling.

477
00:50:53,615 --> 00:50:58,678
l told her you were
on the factory floor. Go ahead.

478
00:50:58,853 --> 00:51:02,083
